    <title>Combined summary - Relax OP_RETURN standardness restrictions</title>
    <updated>2025-05-06T02:51:49.176858+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/rhfyCHr4RfaEalbfGejVdolYCVWIyf84PT2062DQbs5-eU8BPYty5sGyvI3hKeRZQtVC7rn_ugjUWFnWCymz9e9Chbn7FjWJePllFhZRKYk=@protonmail.com/T/#u#mb13230a0c1c39b82b74f928791726d6a254063a4" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The discussion within the Bitcoin development community regarding OP_RETURN outputs has been comprehensive, touching on various aspects ranging from technical implementation to policy implications. Initially, the conversation delves into the historical context and current limitations surrounding OP_RETURN outputs, which are capped both in size and quantity per transaction. This restriction was initially put in place with the intent to discourage blockchain bloat by limiting the capacity for non-transactional data storage.

However, as the dialogue unfolds, it becomes evident that these limitations have spurred developers to seek alternative methods to embed data within transactions, sometimes leading to practices that might be more detrimental than the direct use of OP_RETURN for data storage. For instance, the Citrea bridge named Clementine's approach to embedding data within Taproot outputs is highlighted as a creative yet unintended consequence of the existing constraints.

In response to these developments, there's a proposition to reevaluate and potentially relax the restrictions on OP_RETURN outputs. This proposal suggests first removing the limit on the size of scriptPubKey for OP_RETURN outputs, aiming to mitigate the promotion of less desirable methods for data embedding. Following this, it advocates for lifting the constraint on the number of OP_RETURN outputs per transaction, further emphasizing the need to reconsider the network's approach to on-chain data storage.

This ongoing debate reflects a broader consideration of how best to balance the utility and efficiency of the Bitcoin blockchain with the original goals of minimizing unnecessary data storage. The conversation underscores an evolving understanding within the development community of the implications of standardness rules and the complexities involved in managing a decentralized network. As developers continue to navigate these challenges, the discourse around OP_RETURN outputs remains a focal point for discussions on innovation, security, and the future direction of Bitcoin protocol enhancements.</summary>
